{"title_page": "Faith (The Weeknd song)", "text_new": "{{short description|2020 song by The Weeknd}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name     = Faith\n| cover    = \n| alt      =\n| type     = song\n| artist   = [[The Weeknd]]\n| album    = [[After Hours (The Weeknd album)|After Hours]]\n| released = {{Start date|2020|03|20}}\n| format   =\n* [[Music download|Digital download]]\n* [[Streaming media|streaming]]\n| recorded = \n| studio   = XO Studios (Hidden Hills, CA)\n\n| genre    = <!-- Sourced in references found throughout the body. -->\n*[[Alternative R&B]]\n*[[synthwave]]\n| length   = {{duration|m=4|s=43}}\n| label    = \n* [[XO (record label)|XO]]\n* [[Republic Records|Republic]]\n| writer   = \n* [[The Weeknd|Abel Tesfaye]]\n* [[Belly (rapper)|Ahmad Balshe]]\n* [[Metro Boomin|Leland Wayne]]\n* [[Illangelo|Carlo Montagnese]]\n| producer = \n* [[Metro Boomin]]\n* [[The Weeknd]]\n* [[Illangelo]]\n| misc     = \n}}\n\"'''Faith'''\" is a song by Canadian singer [[The Weeknd]] from his fourth studio album ''[[After Hours (The Weeknd album)|After Hours]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rap-up.com/2020/03/17/the-weeknd-after-hours-tracklist/|title=The Weeknd Reveals 'After Hours' Tracklist|website=Rap-Up|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> The track was teased multiple times throughout the pre-release promotional material for the album, with the song's intro first being shown on February 13, 2020, through the ''After Hours'' teaser titled ''Album Title''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.popdust.com/the-weeknd-new-album-2645142098.html|title=The Weeknd Dramatically Announces His New Album|website=Popdust|last=Cummings-Grady|first=Mackenzie|date=February 13, 2020|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>  Its second verse and outro were teased on the album's self-titled short film, which was released on March 4, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/music/news/the-weeknd-after-hours-short-film-watch-video-1203524075/|title=Watch The Weeknd's Disturbing Short Film for 'After Hours'|website=Variety|last=Aswad|first=Jem|date=March 4, 2020|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> The song was officially released on March 20, 2020, alongside the rest of its parent album.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hypebeast.com/2020/3/the-weeknd-after-hours-album-spotify-listening-session|title=The Weeknd Is Hosting an 'After Hours' Listening Session on Spotify|website=Hypebeast|last=Ingvaldsen|first=Torsten|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> The Weeknd co-wrote the song with Canadian rapper [[Belly (rapper)|Belly]] and its producers [[Metro Boomin]] and [[Illangelo]].<ref name=\"Tidal\"/>\n\n==Background and release==\nIn early February 2020, The Weeknd released the album teaser titled ''Album Title'', which featured the intro to the album's eighth track \"Faith\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/music/news/weeknd-album-teaser-after-hours-watch-video-1203503446/|title=The Weeknd Drops Teaser for New Album, \u2018After Hours\u2019 (Watch)|first1=Jem|last1=Aswad|first2=Jem|last2=Aswad|date=February 13, 2020|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> Later on March 4, 2020, the album's self-titled short film was released, and it featured the second verse and outro of the aforementioned song.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2020/03/the-weeknd-after-hours-short-film|title=The Weeknd Shares 'After Hours' Short Film|website=Complex|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> The studio version of the song was then released on March 20, 2020, alongside the rest of the album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/9336720/the-weeknd-after-hours-track-list|title=The Weeknd&#39;s &#39;After Hours&#39; Track List: See Here|date=March 17, 2020|website=Billboard|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.xxlmag.com/news/2020/03/the-weeknd-after-hours-album/|title=The Weeknd Drops After Hours Album: Listen to New Songs|first=Trent|last=Fitzgerald|website=XXL Mag|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Lyrics==\nThe lyrics of the song reference the on-and-off relationship Tesfaye has with model [[Bella Hadid]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usmagazine.com/entertainment/news/twitter-thinks-the-weeknd-album-after-hours-is-about-bella-hadid/|title=Twitter Is Convinced The Weeknd\u2019s \u2018Entire\u2019 New Album Is About Bella Hadid|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hollywoodlife.com/2020/03/20/the-weeknd-after-hours-album-bella-hadid-songs/|title=The Weeknd\u2019s Fans Are Convinced That He Drops Multiple References To Bella Hadid In New Album|first=Jason Brow,Jade|last=Boren|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> In the track, The Weeknd sings about his struggles with drugs and his inability to love following the end of the relationship he had with his partner.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dailybruin.com/2020/03/20/album-review-the-weeknd-authentically-portrays-heartache-over-past-heartbreak-in-after-hours/|title=Album review: The Weeknd authentically portrays heartache over past heartbreak in \u2018After Hours\u2019|date=March 20, 2020|website=Daily Bruin|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> Tesfaye discusses in the song's lyrics that he wants no sympathy to be felt for him in his relapse and that he losing faith in his religion because of his renewed drug usage, with him stating on the track that he rather choose [[Las Vegas]]' hedonism over salvation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/9339141/the-weeknd-after-hours-lyrics-decoded|title=The Weeknd&#39;s Most Emotional Lyrics on &#39;After Hours&#39;|date=March 20, 2020|website=Billboard|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genius.com/a/how-las-vegas-shapes-the-weeknd-s-after-hours|title=How Las Vegas Shapes The Weeknd\u2019s \u2018After Hours\u2019|website=Genius|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> He mentions drugs such as [[xanax]] and [[lean (recreational drug)|lean]], and that if he overdoses, he wants his partner to be right beside him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://justrandomthings.com/2020/03/20/the-weeknd-faith-lyrics-meaning-song-review/|title=The Weeknd - Faith &#124; Lyrics Meaning & Song Review|first=Adam|last=McDonald|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> In the track, references to the hit singles \"[[Purple Rain (song)|Purple Rain]]\" by [[Prince (musician)|Prince]], \"[[Losing My Religion]]\" by [[R.E.M.]], and \"[[Sicko Mode]]\" by [[Travis Scott]] are made as well.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/thepitch/6-takeaways-from-the-weeknds-new-album-after-hours/|title=6 Takeaways From the Weeknd\u2019s New Album, After Hours|website=Pitchfork|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rap-up.com/2020/03/20/drake-shows-love-the-weeknd-livestream/|title=Drake Shows Love to The Weeknd During Livestream|website=Rap-Up|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nThe song was noted as a being a highlight from the album by critics,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/the-weeknd-is-losing-his-faith-on-after-hours-listen-new-song.1986624.html|title=The Weeknd Is Losing His \"Faith\" On \"After Hours\": Listen|website=HotNewHipHop|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> with Max Cea from ''[[GQ]]'' calling it one of his masterworks in the [[alternative R&B]] genre. In Cea's review of the song, he applauds The Weeknd's writing and singing, as well as the production of the track, giving praise the song's outro which directly leads into \"[[Blinding Lights]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gq.com/story/the-weeknd-after-hours-best-song|title=The Best Song on The Weeknd's New Album, 'After Hours,' Is\u2026|first=Max|last=Cea|website=GQ|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> Jon Dolan from ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' also gave a positive review for the song, describing it as being magisterial and giving particular praise to Tesfaye's vocals and [[Metro Boomin]]'s production.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/the-weeknd-after-hours-971129/|title=The Weeknd Is Alone Again, Naturally, on 'After Hours'|first1=Jon|last1=Dolan|first2=Jon|last2=Dolan|date=March 23, 2020|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> The song's [[synthwave]] sound also received comparisons to the work done by [[Kavinsky]] on his debut single \"[[Nightcall (song)|Nightcall]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theringer.com/music/2020/3/25/21194498/the-weeknd-after-hours-review|title=\u2018After Hours\u2019 Is the Weeknd\u2019s Most Accomplished Work Yet|first=Micah|last=Peters|date=March 25, 2020|website=The Ringer|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\nFollowing the releasing of its parent album, \"Faith\" debuted at number 45 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] dated April 4, 2020. It was the twelfth highest charting track from ''After Hours''.<ref name=\"Hot 100 Peak\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/amp/articles/business/chart-beat/9346588/every-song-weeknd-after-hours-hot-100|title=Every Song From The Weeknd's 'After Hours' Is on the Hot 100|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Zellener|first=Xander|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits adapted from [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]].<ref name=\"Tidal\">{{cite web|url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/134815153|title=After Hours / The Weeknd \u2013 Tidal|website=[[Tidal (service)|Tidal]]|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> \n* [[The Weeknd]] \u2013 vocals, songwriting, production\n* [[Metro Boomin]] \u2013 songwriting, production\n* [[Illangelo]] \u2013 songwriting, production\n* [[Belly (rapper)|Belly]] \u2013 songwriting\n* Dave Kutch \u2013 mastering\n* Kevin Peterson \u2013 mastering\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2020)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{single chart|Canada|43|artist=The Weeknd|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Czechdigital|65|year=2020|week=13|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Estonia ([[Eesti Tipp-40]])<ref name=\"estonianchart\">{{Cite web|url=https://ekspress.delfi.ee/areen/eesti-tipp-40-muusikas-selle-nadala-kangelased-on-the-weeknd-ja-ag?id=89401195|title=Eesti Tipp-40 Muusikas: Selle n\u00e4dala kangelased on The Weeknd ja AG|language=Estonian|last=Nestor|first=Siim|website=[[Eesti Ekspress]]|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n| 34\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| France ([[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|SNEP]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://snepmusique.com/les-tops/le-top-de-la-semaine/top-albums/?semaine=13?&annee=2020&categorie=Top%20Singles|title=Top Singles (Week 13, 2020)|publisher=[[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique]]|language=French|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n| 85\n|-\n{{single chart|Italy|90|artist=The Weeknd|song=Faith|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Portugal|56|artist=The Weeknd|song=Faith|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Slovakdigital|26|year=2020|week=13|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Sweden|81|artist=The Weeknd|song=Faith|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|UKstreaming|47|date=20200327|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardhot100|45|artist=The Weeknd|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardrandbhiphop|24|artist=The Weeknd|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US [[Rolling Stone Top 100|''Rolling Stone'' Top 100]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/charts/songs/2020-01-16/|title=Top 100 Songs|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n| 17\n|}\n\n==Release history==\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Region\n! scope=\"col\"| Date\n! scope=\"col\"| Format\n! scope=\"col\"| Label(s)\n! scope=\"col\"| {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Various\n| March 20, 2020\n| {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[Streaming media|streaming]]}}\n| {{hlist|[[XO (record label)|XO]]|[[Republic Records|Republic]]}}\n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/listen-to-the-weeknds-new-album-after-hours/|title=Listen to the Weeknd\u2019s New Album After Hours|website=Pitchfork|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|the-weeknd|faith}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n* {{YouTube|RcS_8-a-sMg|Faith (Audio)}}\n\n{{The Weeknd}}\n\n[[Category:2020 songs]]\n[[Category:The Weeknd songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Belly (rapper)]]\n[[Category:Songs written by The Weeknd]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by The Weeknd]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Metro Boomin]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Metro Boomin]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Illangelo]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Illangelo]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2020 song by The Weeknd}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name     = Faith\n| cover    = \n| alt      =\n| type     = song\n| artist   = [[The Weeknd]]\n| album    = [[After Hours (The Weeknd album)|After Hours]]\n| released = {{Start date|2020|03|20}}\n| format   =\n* [[Music download|Digital download]]\n* [[Streaming media|streaming]]\n| recorded = \n| studio   = XO Studios (Hidden Hills, CA)\n\n| genre    = <!-- Sourced in references found throughout the body. -->\n*[[Alternative R&B]]\n*[[synthwave]]\n| length   = {{duration|m=4|s=43}}\n| label    = \n* [[XO (record label)|XO]]\n* [[Republic Records|Republic]]\n| writer   = \n* [[The Weeknd|Abel Tesfaye]]\n* [[Belly (rapper)|Ahmad Balshe]]\n* [[Metro Boomin|Leland Wayne]]\n* [[Illangelo|Carlo Montagnese]]\n| producer = \n* [[Metro Boomin]]\n* [[The Weeknd]]\n* [[Illangelo]]\n| misc     = \n}}\n\"'''Faith'''\" is a song by Canadian singer [[The Weeknd]] from his fourth studio album ''[[After Hours (The Weeknd album)|After Hours]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rap-up.com/2020/03/17/the-weeknd-after-hours-tracklist/|title=The Weeknd Reveals 'After Hours' Tracklist|website=Rap-Up|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> The track was teased multiple times throughout the pre-release promotional material for the album, with the song's intro first being shown on February 13, 2020, through the ''After Hours'' teaser titled ''Album Title''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.popdust.com/the-weeknd-new-album-2645142098.html|title=The Weeknd Dramatically Announces His New Album|website=Popdust|last=Cummings-Grady|first=Mackenzie|date=February 13, 2020|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>  Its second verse and outro were teased on the album's self-titled short film, which was released on March 4, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/music/news/the-weeknd-after-hours-short-film-watch-video-1203524075/|title=Watch The Weeknd's Disturbing Short Film for 'After Hours'|website=Variety|last=Aswad|first=Jem|date=March 4, 2020|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> The song was officially released on March 20, 2020, alongside the rest of its parent album.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hypebeast.com/2020/3/the-weeknd-after-hours-album-spotify-listening-session|title=The Weeknd Is Hosting an 'After Hours' Listening Session on Spotify|website=Hypebeast|last=Ingvaldsen|first=Torsten|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> The Weeknd co-wrote the song with Canadian rapper [[Belly (rapper)|Belly]] and its producers [[Metro Boomin]] and [[Illangelo]].<ref name=\"Tidal\"/>\n\n==Background and release==\nIn early February 2020, The Weeknd released the album teaser titled ''Album Title'', which featured the intro to the album's eighth track \"Faith\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/music/news/weeknd-album-teaser-after-hours-watch-video-1203503446/|title=The Weeknd Drops Teaser for New Album, \u2018After Hours\u2019 (Watch)|first1=Jem|last1=Aswad|first2=Jem|last2=Aswad|date=February 13, 2020|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> Later on March 4, 2020, the album's self-titled short film was released, and it featured the second verse and outro of the aforementioned song.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2020/03/the-weeknd-after-hours-short-film|title=The Weeknd Shares 'After Hours' Short Film|website=Complex|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> The studio version of the song was then released on March 20, 2020, alongside the rest of the album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/9336720/the-weeknd-after-hours-track-list|title=The Weeknd&#39;s &#39;After Hours&#39; Track List: See Here|date=March 17, 2020|website=Billboard|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.xxlmag.com/news/2020/03/the-weeknd-after-hours-album/|title=The Weeknd Drops After Hours Album: Listen to New Songs|first=Trent|last=Fitzgerald|website=XXL Mag|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Lyrics==\nThe lyrics of the song reference the on-and-off relationship Tesfaye has with model [[Bella Hadid]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usmagazine.com/entertainment/news/twitter-thinks-the-weeknd-album-after-hours-is-about-bella-hadid/|title=Twitter Is Convinced The Weeknd\u2019s \u2018Entire\u2019 New Album Is About Bella Hadid|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hollywoodlife.com/2020/03/20/the-weeknd-after-hours-album-bella-hadid-songs/|title=The Weeknd\u2019s Fans Are Convinced That He Drops Multiple References To Bella Hadid In New Album|first=Jason Brow,Jade|last=Boren|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> In the track, The Weeknd sings about his struggles with drugs and his inability to love following the end of the relationship he had with his partner.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dailybruin.com/2020/03/20/album-review-the-weeknd-authentically-portrays-heartache-over-past-heartbreak-in-after-hours/|title=Album review: The Weeknd authentically portrays heartache over past heartbreak in \u2018After Hours\u2019|date=March 20, 2020|website=Daily Bruin|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> Tesfaye discusses in the song's lyrics that he wants no sympathy to be felt for him in his relapse and that he losing faith in his religion because of his renewed drug usage, with him stating on the track that he rather choose [[Las Vegas]]' hedonism over salvation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/9339141/the-weeknd-after-hours-lyrics-decoded|title=The Weeknd&#39;s Most Emotional Lyrics on &#39;After Hours&#39;|date=March 20, 2020|website=Billboard|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genius.com/a/how-las-vegas-shapes-the-weeknd-s-after-hours|title=How Las Vegas Shapes The Weeknd\u2019s \u2018After Hours\u2019|website=Genius|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> He mentions drugs such as [[xanax]] and [[lean (recreational drug)|lean]], and that if he overdoses, he wants his partner to be right beside him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://justrandomthings.com/2020/03/20/the-weeknd-faith-lyrics-meaning-song-review/|title=The Weeknd - Faith &#124; Lyrics Meaning & Song Review|first=Adam|last=McDonald|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> In the track, references to the hit singles \"[[Purple Rain (song)|Purple Rain]]\" by [[Prince (musician)|Prince]], \"[[Losing My Religion]]\" by [[R.E.M.]], and \"[[Sicko Mode]]\" by [[Travis Scott]] are made as well.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/thepitch/6-takeaways-from-the-weeknds-new-album-after-hours/|title=6 Takeaways From the Weeknd\u2019s New Album, After Hours|website=Pitchfork|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rap-up.com/2020/03/20/drake-shows-love-the-weeknd-livestream/|title=Drake Shows Love to The Weeknd During Livestream|website=Rap-Up|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nThe song was noted as a being a highlight from the album by critics,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/the-weeknd-is-losing-his-faith-on-after-hours-listen-new-song.1986624.html|title=The Weeknd Is Losing His \"Faith\" On \"After Hours\": Listen|website=HotNewHipHop|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> with Max Cea from ''[[GQ]]'' calling it one of his masterworks in the [[alternative R&B]] genre. In Cea's review of the song, he applauds the The Weeknd's writing and singing, as well as the production of the track, giving praise the song's outro which directly leads into \"[[Blinding Lights]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gq.com/story/the-weeknd-after-hours-best-song|title=The Best Song on The Weeknd's New Album, 'After Hours,' Is\u2026|first=Max|last=Cea|website=GQ|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> Jon Dolan from ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' also gave a positive review for the song, describing it as being magisterial and giving particular praise to Tesfaye's vocals and [[Metro Boomin]]'s production.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/the-weeknd-after-hours-971129/|title=The Weeknd Is Alone Again, Naturally, on 'After Hours'|first1=Jon|last1=Dolan|first2=Jon|last2=Dolan|date=March 23, 2020|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> The song's [[synthwave]] sound also received comparisons to the work done by [[Kavinsky]] on his debut single \"[[Nightcall (song)|Nightcall]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theringer.com/music/2020/3/25/21194498/the-weeknd-after-hours-review|title=\u2018After Hours\u2019 Is the Weeknd\u2019s Most Accomplished Work Yet|first=Micah|last=Peters|date=March 25, 2020|website=The Ringer|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\nFollowing the releasing of its parent album, \"Faith\" debuted at number 45 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] dated April 4, 2020. It was the twelfth highest charting track from ''After Hours''.<ref name=\"Hot 100 Peak\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/amp/articles/business/chart-beat/9346588/every-song-weeknd-after-hours-hot-100|title=Every Song From The Weeknd's 'After Hours' Is on the Hot 100|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Zellener|first=Xander|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits adapted from [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]].<ref name=\"Tidal\">{{cite web|url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/134815153|title=After Hours / The Weeknd \u2013 Tidal|website=[[Tidal (service)|Tidal]]|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> \n* [[The Weeknd]] \u2013 vocals, songwriting, production\n* [[Metro Boomin]] \u2013 songwriting, production\n* [[Illangelo]] \u2013 songwriting, production\n* [[Belly (rapper)|Belly]] \u2013 songwriting\n* Dave Kutch \u2013 mastering\n* Kevin Peterson \u2013 mastering\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2020)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{single chart|Canada|43|artist=The Weeknd|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Czechdigital|65|year=2020|week=13|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Estonia ([[Eesti Tipp-40]])<ref name=\"estonianchart\">{{Cite web|url=https://ekspress.delfi.ee/areen/eesti-tipp-40-muusikas-selle-nadala-kangelased-on-the-weeknd-ja-ag?id=89401195|title=Eesti Tipp-40 Muusikas: Selle n\u00e4dala kangelased on The Weeknd ja AG|language=Estonian|last=Nestor|first=Siim|website=[[Eesti Ekspress]]|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n| 34\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| France ([[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|SNEP]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://snepmusique.com/les-tops/le-top-de-la-semaine/top-albums/?semaine=13?&annee=2020&categorie=Top%20Singles|title=Top Singles (Week 13, 2020)|publisher=[[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique]]|language=French|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n| 85\n|-\n{{single chart|Italy|90|artist=The Weeknd|song=Faith|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Portugal|56|artist=The Weeknd|song=Faith|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Slovakdigital|26|year=2020|week=13|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Sweden|81|artist=The Weeknd|song=Faith|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|UKstreaming|47|date=20200327|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardhot100|45|artist=The Weeknd|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardrandbhiphop|24|artist=The Weeknd|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US [[Rolling Stone Top 100|''Rolling Stone'' Top 100]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/charts/songs/2020-01-16/|title=Top 100 Songs|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n| 17\n|}\n\n==Release history==\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Region\n! scope=\"col\"| Date\n! scope=\"col\"| Format\n! scope=\"col\"| Label(s)\n! scope=\"col\"| {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Various\n| March 20, 2020\n| {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[Streaming media|streaming]]}}\n| {{hlist|[[XO (record label)|XO]]|[[Republic Records|Republic]]}}\n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/listen-to-the-weeknds-new-album-after-hours/|title=Listen to the Weeknd\u2019s New Album After Hours|website=Pitchfork|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|the-weeknd|faith}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n* {{YouTube|RcS_8-a-sMg|Faith (Audio)}}\n\n{{The Weeknd}}\n\n[[Category:2020 songs]]\n[[Category:The Weeknd songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Belly (rapper)]]\n[[Category:Songs written by The Weeknd]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by The Weeknd]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Metro Boomin]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Metro Boomin]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Illangelo]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Illangelo]