r;\" |2001\n| <center>Softball</center>\n|-\n|'''Idel V\u00e1zquez''' \n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2001\n| <center>Softball</center>\n|-\n|'''[[Ivelisse Echevarr\u00eda]]''' \n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2003\n| <center>Softball</center>\n|-\n|'''Betty Segarra ''' \n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2004\n| <center>Softball</center>\n|-\n|'''Clara V\u00e1zquez''' \n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2005\n| <center>Softball</center>\n|-\n|'''Lissette \u201cKiki\u201d Gaetan''' \n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2009\n| <center>Table Tennis</center>\n|-\n|'''Grace Vald\u00e9z ''' \n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |1968\n| <center>Tennis</center>\n|-\n|'''Mady Romeu''' \n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |1975\n| <center>Tennis</center>\n|-\n|'''Martita Torros''' \n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |1984\n| <center>Tennis</center>\n|-\n|'''Josefina Cabrera''' \n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |1985\n| <center>Tennis</center>\n|-\n|'''Cindy Colbert''' \n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |1990\n| <center>Tennis</center>\n|-\n|'''Crissy Gonz\u00e1lez''' \n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |1994\n| <center>Tennis</center>\n|-\n|'''Marilda Julia''' \n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2000\n| <center>Tennis</center>\n|-\n|'''[[Gigi Fern\u00e1ndez|Beatr\u00edz (Gigi) Fern\u00e1ndez]]''' \n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2007\n| <center>Tennis</center>\n|-\n|'''[[Emilie Viqueira]]''' \n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2011\n| <center>Tennis</center>\n|-\n|'''Flor Zengotita''' \n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |1979\n| <center>Volleyball</center>\n|-\n|'''Iris Toro''' \n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |1985\n| <center>Volleyball</center>\n|-\n|'''Carole D\u00edaz''' \n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |1986\n| <center>Volleyball</center>\n|-\n|'''Bessie Figueroa''' \n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |1994\n| <center>Volleyball</center>\n|-\n|'''Betty Garc\u00eda''' \n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |1973\n| <center>Sports Promoter</center>\n|-\n|'''Rosarito L\u00f3pez Cepero''' \n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |1998\n| <center>Sports Promoter</center>\n|-\n|}\n</center>\n\n[[Laura Daniela Lloreda]] is a Puerto Rican who represented [[Mexico]] at various international women's volleyball competitions and played professional volleyball both in Mexico and in Puerto Rico,<ref>http://www.baylorbears.com/sports/w-volley/mtt/lloreda_lauradaniela00.html</ref> and [[Ada V\u00e9lez]] is a Puerto Rican former boxer who became the country's first professional women's world boxing champion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.womenboxing.com/biog/avelez.htm|title=Women's Boxing: Ada Velez Biography|website=www.womenboxing.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, [[Carla Malatrasi]] and her husband [[Enrique Figueroa]] won a gold medal in sailing in the Pan Am Hobie competition celebrated in [[Winnipeg]], Canada. In 2002, Carla and her husband came in 3rd place in the Hobie Racing-ISAF Sailing Games H-16 which took place in [[Marseille]], France, in which they went against 36 teams representing 20 nations. On March 3, 2003 the Senate of Puerto Rico honored Carla Malatrasi and her husband Enrique, by recognizing their achievements<ref name=\"Hobie\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.hobieclass.com/default.asp?Page=1913|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060813115507/http://www.hobieclass.com/default.asp?Page=1913|url-status=dead|title=Past Champions|archivedate=August 13, 2006}}</ref><ref name=\"Hobie\"/>\n[[File:Puig US16 (38) (29236398233).jpg|150px|thumb|Monica Puig won the first Olympic gold medal for Puerto Rico]]\nPuerto Rico has participated in the Olympics, since the [[1948 Summer Olympics]], which were celebrated in London, as an independent nation. However, since Puerto Ricans have American citizenship, Puerto Rican athletes have the option of representing Puerto Rico or moving to the United States where after living there for 3 years or more they can represent that country in the games. Some Puerto Ricans, such as [[Gigi Fern\u00e1ndez]] in tennis, have won gold medals for the U.S. Also, women who are of Puerto Rican heritage are considered by the Government of Puerto Rico to be \"Puerto Rican Citizens\". Since 2007, the Government of Puerto Rico has been issuing \"[[Puerto Rican citizenship|Certificates of Puerto Rican Citizenship]]\" to anyone born in Puerto Rico or to anyone born outside of Puerto Rico with at least one parent who was born in Puerto Rico.<ref name=\"aldia.microjuris.com\"/>\n\n[[Kristina Brandi]] represented Puerto Rico in the [[2004 Summer Olympics]] in [[Athens]], Greece. She became the first tennis player representing Puerto Rico to win a singles match in an Olympic when she beat [[Jelena Kostani\u0107]] from [[Croatia]] (7\u20135 and 6\u20131). She lost in the second round to Russian [[Anastasia Myskina]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/br/kristina-brandi-1.html|title=Kristina Brandi Bio, Stats, and Results|website=Olympics at Sports-Reference.com}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2016 Summer Olympics]] in Rio de Janeiro, [[Monica Puig]] made Olympic history<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetorch/2016/08/13/489921211/monica-puig-makes-olympic-history-winning-puerto-rico-s-first-gold-medal|title=Monica Puig Makes Olympic History, Winning Puerto Rico's First Gold Medal|website=NPR.org}}</ref> when she became the first person to win an Olympic gold medal for Puerto Rico by defeating Germany's [[Angelique Kerber]] in the [[Tennis at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's Singles|women's singles tennis]] final. She became the first Puerto Rican female medalist in any sport.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/sport/live/2016/aug/13/rio-olympics-2016-us-medals-continue-to-flow-in-pool-as-solo-rant-causes-a-storm Rio \"Olympics: Monica Puig wins Puerto Rico's first ever gold \u2013 live!\"], ''The Guardian''</ref>\n\nThe following table has a list of the Puerto Rican women, including women of Puerto Rican ancestry, who won Olympic medals.\n\n<center>\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background-color:Gold\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |[[File:Flag of Puerto Rico.svg|25px]]<br/>'''Puerto Rican Women Olympic Medallists'''\n|- \n|}\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Number\n!Name\n!Medal/s \n!Sport\n!Year and place\n!Country represented \n|-\n|1\n|'''[[Gigi Fern\u00e1ndez]]'''\n|<center>'''Gold (2)'''</center>\n|<center>Women's Doubles Tennis</center>\n|1992 Barcelona, Spain<br/>1996 Atlanta, United States\n|{{flagu|United States}}\n|-\n|2\n|'''[[Lisa Fernandez]]''' \n|<center>'''Gold (3)'''</center>\n|<center>Softball</center>\n|1996 Atlanta, United States<br/>2000 Sydney, Australia<br/>2004 Athens, Greece\n|{{flagu|United States}}\n|-\n|3\n|'''[[Julie Chu]]'''\n|<center>'''Silver (3)''', '''Bronze'''</center>\n|<center>Women's Ice Hockey</center>\n|2002 Salt Lake City, United States<br/>2006 Turin, Italy<br/>2010 Vancouver, Canada<br/>2014 Sochi, Russia\n|{{flagu|United States}}\n|-\n|4\n|'''[[Maritza Correia]]'''\n|<center>'''Silver'''\n|<center>Swimming 4 \u00d7 100 m Freestyle</center>\n|2004 Athens, Greece</center>\n|{{flagu|United States}}\n|-\n|5\n|'''[[Kyla Ross ]]'''\n|<center>'''Gold'''</center>\n|<center>400m Women's Gymnastics</center>\n|2012 London, United Kingdom\n|{{flagu|United States}}\n|-\n|6\n|'''[[Jessica Steffens]]'''\n|<center>'''Silver''', '''Gold'''</center>\n|<center>Water Polo</center>\n|2008 Beijing, China<br/>2012 London, United Kingdom\n|{{flagu|United States}}\n|-\n|7\n|'''[[Maggie Steffens]]'''\n|<center> '''Gold (2)'''</center>\n|<center>Water Polo</center>\n|2012 London, United Kingdom<br/>2016 Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n|{{flagu|United States}}\n|-\n|8\n|'''[[Laurie Hernandez]]'''\n|<center> '''Gold''', '''Silver'''</center>\n|<center>Women's Gymnastics (G)<br/>Balance Beam (S)</center>\n|2016 Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n|{{flagu|United States}}\n|-\n|9\n|'''[[Monica Puig]]'''\n|<center> '''Gold'''</center>\n|<center>Women's Singles Tennis</center>\n|2016 Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n|{{PUR}}\n|-\n|}\n</center>\n\n<center>\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background-color:Gold\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |[[File:Flag of Puerto Rico.svg|25px]]<br/>'''Total Olympic medals'''\n|-\n|}\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Total of medals for {{PUR}}\n!Gold\n!Silver\n!Bronze\n|-\n|<center>1</center>\n|<center>1</center>\n|<center>0</center>\n|<center>0</center>\n|-\n!Total of medals for the {{flagu|United States}}\n!Gold\n!Silver\n!Bronze\n|-\n|<center>17</center>\n|<center>10</center>\n|<center>6</center>\n|<center>1</center>\n|-\n!Total of medals\n!Gold\n!Silver\n!Bronze\n|-\n|<center>18</center>\n|<center>11</center>\n|<center>6</center>\n|<center>1</center>\n|-\n|}\n</center>\n{{Further|Sports in Puerto Rico}}\n\n==Puerto Rican women rebuilding Puerto Rico==\nAfter [[Hurricane Maria]], many women were the driving force to starting up the rebuilding of the island. They have \"waded into flooded neighborhoods to extricate the abandoned, and put together soup kitchens to feed the hungry. They\u2019ve canvassed their communities in order to diagnose the most critical needs\u2014street by street, mountain by mountain, house by house, family by family\u2014and have returned when they said they would with supplies and support.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vogue.com/projects/13542078/puerto-rico-after-hurricane-maria-2/|title=After the Hurricane, Women Are Rebuilding Puerto Rico|first=Mariel Cruz, Richard|last=Mosse|date=March 8, 2018|website=Vogue}}</ref> Small, female-led organizations were the creating fundraisers and even went out on foot to retrieve supplies for suffering families. They were also the driving emotional force for the victims of the disaster, offering some sort of peace to their devastated communities. These same women have been calling out unfair leadership and ignorance in the United States and have empowered the island when their leaders could not.\n\n==Governmental recognition's==\n===Women's week in Puerto Rico===\nOn June 2, 1976, the Legislative Assembly of Puerto Rico approved law number 102 that declared every March 2 \"D\u00eda Internacional de la Mujer\" (International Women's Day) as a tribute to the Puerto Rican women. However, the government of Puerto Rico decided that it would only be proper that a week instead of a day be dedicated in tribute to the accomplishments and contributions of the Puerto Rican women. Therefore, on September 16, 2004, the Legislative Assembly of Puerto Rico passed law number 327, which declares the second week of the month of March the \"Semana de la Mujer en Puerto Rico\" (Women's week in Puerto Rico).<ref>[http://www.lexjuris.com/lexlex/Leyes2004/lexl2004327.htm Ley N\u00fam. 327 del a\u00f1o 2004], retrieved October 3, 2013</ref><ref>[http://www.primerahora.com/noticias/gobierno-politica/nota/monumentosalamujeryalosmaestrosenelcapitolio-624835/ \"Monumentos a la mujer y a los maestros en el Capitolio\"], ''[[Primera Hora (Puerto Rico)|Primera Hora]]''</ref>\n\nIn 2002, the [[Monumento a la Mujer]] (Monument to Women), a statue commemorating the contributions of the Puerto Rican women to the [[Puerto Rican people|Puerto Rican]] society was unveiled at the fork of [[PR-123|Calle Marina]] and [[PR-503|Calle Mayor Cantera]], in [[Ponce, Puerto Rico]], next to [[Parque Urbano Dora Col\u00f3n Clavell]], in [[Cuarto (Ponce)|Barrio Cuarto]]. It depicts a young woman with her right arm stretched up high and holding a small depiction of the globe of the [[Earth]] on her hand. The monument was the first and, at the time, the only one of its kind \"in Puerto Rico and the Caribbean\".<ref>Plaque at base of the monument. August 2010.</ref> There is also a time capsule (5 August 1992 to 5 August 2092) that is buried at the back base of the monument.<ref>Luis A. Rodriguez Vazquez. ''Vida, Pasion y Muerte a Orillas del Rio Baramaya.'' 2009. p.90.</ref><ref>NotiSur. Ponce, Puerto Rico. 6\u201312 August 1998.</ref>\n\nThe dedicatory plaque on the monument has an inscription that reads (Note: English translation is not part of the inscription, and it is given here to the right):\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; margin: 1em auto 1em auto\"\n|+\"Monumento a la Mujer\"\n|-\n! Spanish<br />(original version)\n! English<br />translation\n|-\n|<poem> A LA MUJER\n\n''Con este Monumento se honra''\n''a la Mujer, que por su virtud,''\n''esfuerzo y altas cualidades ha''\n''contribuido brillantemente a''\n''forjar la Historia y la Cultura,''\n''logrando asi un sitial de''\n''igualdad en el Mundo, siendo''\n''siempre imagen de Belleza y''\n''transmisora de la Vida.''\n''5 de agosto de 1992''\n</poem>\n|<poem> TO THE WOMEN\n\n''This Monument honors''\n''the Women, who for their virtue,''\n''effort and high qualities has''\n''contributed brilliantly to''\n''forge History and Culture,''\n''thus achieving a place of''\n''equality in the World, being''\n''always an image of Beauty and''\n''the transmitter of Life.''\n''5 August 1992''</poem>\n|-\n|}\n\nIn May 29, 2014, The Legislative Assembly of Puerto Rico honored 12 illustrious women with plaques in the \"La Plaza en Honor a la Mujer Puertorrique\u00f1a\" (Plaza in Honor of Puerto Rican Women) in San Juan. They were the first to be honored. According to the plaques the following 12 women, who by virtue of their merits and legacies, stand out in the history of Puerto Rico. They are:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://temascontroversialesvargas.blogspot.com/2014/05/la-mujer-en-nuestra-historia_2376.html}|title=La Mujer en nuestra historia}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:left\"\n|- \"\n! scope=\"col\" | Name !! scope=\"col\" | Noted for !! scope=\"col\" | Year honored\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | [[Lola Rodr\u00edguez de Ti\u00f3]] || First Puerto Rican-born woman poet to establish herself a reputation as a great poet, a believer in women's rights, committed to the abolition of slavery and the independence of Puerto Rico.||<center>2014</center>\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | [[Luisa Capetillo]]|| Writer, labor organizer and an anarchist who fought for workers and women's rights.||<center>2014</center>\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |[[Felisa Rinc\u00f3n de Gautier]] ||The first woman to be elected as the Mayor of a capital city in The Americas. ||<center>2014</center>\n|-\n|scope=\"row\" | Sor [[Isolina Ferr\u00e9]]|| Known as the \"Mother Teresa of Puerto Rico\", she received the Presidential Medal of Freedom in recognition of her humanitarian work. ||<center>2014</center>\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | [[Rebekah Colberg]] ||Known as the \"Mother of Women's Sports in Puerto Rico\"||<center>2014</center>\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | [[Josefina Barcel\u00f3 Bird de Romero]]||Civic leader and politician, leader of the Liberal Party of Puerto Rico. ||<center>2014</center>\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | [[Mar\u00eda Libertad G\u00f3mez Garriga]] ||Educator, community leader, and politician. ||<center>2014</center>\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | [[Mar\u00eda Luisa Arcelay|Mar\u00eda Luisa Arcelay de la Rosa]] ||Educator, businesswoman and politician. She was first woman in Puerto Rico to be elected to a government legislative body. ||<center>2014</center>\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |[[Mar\u00eda Mart\u00ednez Acosta de P\u00e9rez Almiroty]]||Educator, clubwoman and the first woman to be elected senator in Puerto Rico. ||<center>2014</center>\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | [[Julia de Burgos]] || Poet, advocate of Puerto Rican independence, and civil rights activist for women and African/Afro-Caribbean writers.||<center>2014</center>\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |[[Sylvia Rexach]] || Comedy scriptwriter, poet, singer and composer of boleros.||<center>2014</center>\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | [[Gigi Fern\u00e1ndez]] ||Professional tennis player, the first Puerto-Rican-born athlete to win an Olympic Gold Medal and the first to be inducted into the International Tennis Hall of Fame. ||<center>2014</center>\n|}\n\nIn 2015, the following women were also honored:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.foronoticioso.com/fn/legislatura-enaltece-legado-de-mujeres-ilustres-en-plaza-en-honor-a-la-mujer-puertorriquena/|title=LEGISLATURA ENALTECE LEGADO DE MUJERES ILUSTRES EN PLAZA EN HONOR A LA MUJER PUERTORRIQUE\u00d1A|date=March 13, 2015|website=Foro Noticioso}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:left\"\n|- \"\n! scope=\"col\" | Name !! scope=\"col\" | Noted for !! scope=\"col\" | Year honored\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | [[Rosario Ferr\u00e9|Rosario Ferr\u00e9 Ram\u00edrez de Arellano]]||Writer, poet, and essayist.||<center>2015</center>\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | Ileana Col\u00f3n Carlo||The first woman to be named Comptroller of Puerto Rico.||<center>2015</center>\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |Celeste Ben\u00edtez ||Educator, journalist and politician. ||<center>2015</center>\n|-\n|scope=\"row\" |[[Velda Gonz\u00e1lez]]||Actress, dancer, comedian, politician and former senator.||<center>2015</center>\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | [[Miriam Naveira|Miriam Naveira de Merly]] || She was the first woman to serve on the Supreme Court of Puerto Rico as well as the first female Chief Justice ||<center>2015</center>\n|}\n\n===Presidential Medal of Freedom===\n\n{{multiple image\n| direction = horizontal\n| width = 80\nFile:PresMedalFreedom.jpg\n|[[Presidential Medal of Freedom]]\nFile:Presidential Citizens Medal.png\n|[[Presidential Citizens Medal]]\n}}\n\nFive Puerto Rican women have been awarded the [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]], an award bestowed by the President of the United States that is considered the highest [[Civilian decorations of the United States|civilian award]] in the United States. The medal recognizes those individuals who have made \"an especially meritorious contribution to the security or national interests of the United States, world peace, cultural or other significant public or private endeavors\".<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">[[s:Executive Order 9586|Executive Order 9586]], signed July 6, 1945; Federal Register 10 FR 8523, July 10, 1945</ref><ref name=\"PMoF\">[http://www.nndb.com/honors/482/000045347/ Presidential Medal of Freedom ], retrieved October 3, 2013</ref> The following Puerto Rican women have been awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom:\n\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* '''[[Antonia Pantojas]]''' \u2013 educator, social worker, feminist, civil rights leader. Awarded in 1996.\n* '''[[Isolina Ferr\u00e9]]''' \u2013 nun. Awarded in 1999.\n* '''[[Rita Moreno]]''' \u2013 actress, singer, and [[List of people who have won Academy, Emmy, Grammy, and Tony Awards|EGOT]] recipient. Awarded in 2004.\n* '''[[Chita Rivera]]''' \u2013 actress, dancer, and singer. Awarded in 2009.\n* '''[[Sylvia Mendez]]''' \u2013 civil rights activist. Awarded in 2011.\n}}\n\n===Presidential Citizens Medal===\nTwo Puerto Rican women have been awarded the [[Presidential Citizens Medal]], an award bestowed by the President of the United States that is considered the second highest civilian award in the United States, second only to the [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]] mentioned before. The medal recognizes individuals \"who have performed exemplary deeds or services for his or her country or fellow citizens.\"<ref name=\"PCM\" />{{failed verification|date=September 2017}} The following Puerto Rican women have been awarded the Presidential Citizens Medal:\n\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* '''[[Helen Rodriguez-Trias]]''' \u2013 pediatrician, educator, and leader in public health. Awarded in 2001.\n* '''[[Victoria Leigh Soto]]''' \u2013 educator who was murdered in the [[Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting]]. while protecting the lives of her students. Posthumously awarded in 2013.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pearce|first1=Matt|title=Sandy Hook teacher Victoria Soto is given a hero's farewell|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2012/dec/19/nation/la-na-nn-sandy-hook-teacher-victoria-soto-hero-20121219 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=December 19, 2012 |accessdate=December 27, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n{{further|List of Puerto Rican Presidential Medal of Freedom recipients|List of Puerto Rican Presidential Citizens Medal recipients}}\n\n===U.S. Postal Service Commemorative Stamps===\n\nTwo women have been honored by the U.S. Postal Service Commemorative Stamp Program. \nOn April 14, 2007, the [[U.S. Postal Service]] unveiled a stamp commemorating the [[Mendez v. Westminster]] case.<ref name=unveiling>{{cite press release\n |url=http://www.usps.com/communications/newsroom/2007stamps/ \n |title=The 2007 Commemorative Stamp Program \n |publisher=United States Postal Service \n |id=Stamp News Release #06-050 \n |date=October 25, 2006 \n |accessdate=April 5, 2007 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090508223851/http://www.usps.com/communications/newsroom/2007stamps/ \n |archivedate=May 8, 2009 \n}}</ref><ref name=ChapmanU_event>{{cite web |url=http://www.chapman.edu/mendez/\n|title=Chapman University Commemorates Mendez v. Westminster 60th Anniversary & U.S. Postage Stamp Unveiling\n|work=Special Events\n|publisher=Chapman University}}</ref> Featured on the stamp are [[Felicitas Mendez]] (maiden name:Gomez), a native of Juncos, Puerto Rico<ref>Frederick P. Aguirre, [http://library.fullcoll.edu/friends/pdfs/Aguirre-MendezvWestminster.pdf \"Mendez v. Westminster School District: How It Affected Brown v. Board of Education\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131012003816/http://library.fullcoll.edu/friends/pdfs/Aguirre-MendezvWestminster.pdf |date=October 12, 2013 }}, ''Journal of Hispanic Higher Education'' 2005; section: The Mendez Lawsuit page 323, retrieved October 11, 2013</ref> and her husband, Gonzalo Mendez. The unveiling took take place during an event at [[Chapman University]] School of Education, Orange County, California, commemorating the 60th anniversary of the landmark case.<ref name=ChapmanU_news>{{cite web \n|url=http://www.chapman.edu/admission/news/news_story.asp?iNewsID=442&strBack=%2FDefault%2Easp\n|title=Chapman Commemorates 60th Anniversary of Mendez v. Westminster Case on April 14\n|date=March 26, 2007\n|publisher=Chapman University |accessdate=April 6, 2007}}</ref>  On September 14, 2010, in a ceremony held in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico|San Juan]], the United States Postal Service honored [[Julia de Burgos]]'s life and literary work with the issuance of a first class postage stamp, the 26th release in the postal system's ''Literary Arts'' series.<ref name=\"nydailynews.com\">[http://www.nydailynews.com/latino/2010/09/15/2010-09-15_untitled__julia15v.html ''Poet Julia de Burgos gets stamp of approval''] from the ''[[New York Daily News]]'' September 15, 2010</ref><ref>[http://www.usps.com/communications/newsroom/2009/pr09_118.htm#julia ''Postal News: 2010 Stamp Program Unveiled''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606082628/http://www.usps.com/communications/newsroom/2009/pr09_118.htm |date=June 6, 2011 }} from ''www.usps.com'' December 30, 2010</ref>\n{{further|List of Puerto Rican women}}\n\n==Gallery of notable Puerto Rican women==\n<gallery>\nFile:Maria de las Mercedes Barbudo, independence leader from Ponce, Puerto Rico, circa 1815 (DSC03896Z).jpg|[[Mar\u00eda de las Mercedes Barbudo]] (1773\u20131849)<br/>Leader of the [[Puerto Rican independence movement]]\nFile:Carmen Garcia Rosado 001.jpg|[[Carmen Garc\u00eda Rosado]]<br/>PFC WACs, author\nFile:CarmenLozanoDurnier.jpg|[[Carmen Lozano Dumler]] (1921\u20132015)<br/>Lieutenant in the WACS\nFile:Mar\u00eda Bibiana Ben\u00edtez.jpg|[[Mar\u00eda Bibiana Ben\u00edtez]] (1783\u20131873)<br/>Puerto Rico's first female poet and playwrights\nFile:Alejandrina Benitez de Gautier.jpg|[[Alejandrina Ben\u00edtez de Gautier]] (1819\u20131879)<br/>Poet\nFile:Mariana Bracetti.jpg|[[Mariana Bracetti]] (1825\u20131903)<br/>Patriot and leader of the Puerto Rican independence revolt, [[Grito de Lares|El Grito de Lares]] in 1868\nFile:Lola Rodriguez de Tio.jpg|[[Lola Rodr\u00edguez de Ti\u00f3]] (1843\u20131924)<br/>Independence advocate and author of the revolutionary version of \"La Borique\u00f1a\"\nFile:Amalia Paoli, soprano puertorr